item.title: [BEAM-12158] "v1.proto" is already registered error for golang dataflow
item.description:
I tried to run wordcount example in go https://beam.apache.org/get-started/quickstart-go/

It worked fine in dev but when I try to run it on GCP dataflow, I got '"v1.proto" is already registered' error and job crashes. 

 

It seems proto definition here is using very generic package name "v1" which I suspect is a cause of issue

https://github.com/apache/beam/blob/v2.28.0/sdks/go/pkg/beam/io/pubsubio/v1/v1.proto

 

Here is log in GCP

I see the issue. It turns out there are a small handful of these protocol buffers, including one for the Go session runner, and for the Dataflow only pubsub IO. I have some time this afternoon and can resolve them properly. Thank you!

https://github.com/apache/beam/pull/14831 should fix this "once and for all". At least, as far as collisions with Go SDK originating protos.

Please be aware that the go v1 pubsub proto is colliding with something, and that something was originally in the project by itself, but prior to PR 14831 is something outside of beam. 

Your paste is also a bit suspicious since for some reason it thinks the latest version is v2.2.1 which is not the case, though the date timestamp does seem accurate to today. https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/apache/beam/sdks/go/pkg/beam?tab=versions 

If the issue persists after the PR is merged to master, please let me know, as I'm unable to reproduce what you're seeing.
This should now be resolved at tip.

Nope, sorry, still not fixed. I did at least get an error that's slightly more explicit this time, though:

 

panic: proto: file "v1.proto" is already registered
    previously from: "github.com/apache/beam/sdks/go/pkg/beam/core/runtime/graphx/v1"
    currently from:  "github.com/apache/beam/sdks/go/pkg/beam/io/pubsubio/v1"

 

I think what's happening is https://github.com/golang/protobuf/issues/1122 - which seems like a really egregious bug in how protobuf is handling registration. Here, I suspect (but have not verified) it's being tripped by something related to the gen.go files running protoc on each file individually.

If I run the wordcount binary with GOLANG_PROTOBUF_REGISTRATION_CONFLICT=warn (workaround from that issue), it seems to work fine.

Steps to reproduce (from an empty $GOPATH)

  • mkdir -p $GOPATH/src/github.com/apache
  • cd $GOPATH/src/github.com/apache
  • git clone https://github.com/apache/beam
  • GO111MODULE='off' go get ./beam/sdks/go/...
  • GO111MODULE='off' go build ./beam/sdks/go/examples/wordcount
  • ./wordcount

Some additional validation of that theory: I ran

protoc -I . --descriptor_set_out=pubsubio_descriptor.txt

from go/pkg/beam/io/pubsubio/v1 (same as what gen.go is doing), and got a FileDescriptorSet where the name was an unqualified "v1.proto":

> cd $PROTOBUF_REPO
> protoc --decode=google.protobuf.FileDescriptorSet src/google/protobuf/descriptor.proto < pubsubio_descriptor.txt
file {
  name: "v1.proto"
  package: "org.apache.beam.sdks.go.pkg.beam.io.pubsubio.v1"
  message_type {
    name: "PubSubPayload"
    [...etc.]
  }
  options {
    go_package: "github.com/apache/beam/sdks/go/pkg/beam/io/pubsubio/v1;v1"
  }
  syntax: "proto3"
}

Wait wait wait wait. It's failing because the file name is v1.proto, and not even checking against the package paths? That seems incredibly brittle?
That's upsettingly silly of that code.
I'll see if I can't rename the files then sometime today. Nothing depends on the files being those names, other than the scripts that invoke them.

A workaround that would solve the problem specifically for proto files in the Beam SDK would be to change the gen.go files to things like:

//go:generate protoc -I ../../../../../../.. sdks/go/pkg/beam/io/pubsubio/v1/v1.proto --go_out=.

...which is also somewhat unpleasant, since every gen.go file will need to include its own path. It might be better to wait for a resolution on the protobuf issue, though.

Yes, it's literally because the filenames have the same basename. The name of the file, relative to -I, is packed into the descriptor set for each proto file, and those relative names must be globally unique across all protos linked into any binary. Since Beam is generating all protos locally from the directories they appear in, they get generated with only the basename, which leads to collisions.

As discussed on the protobuf issue, this is potentially solveable within one repo, but becomes a huge problem anyway as soon you want to import from multiple places. I'm no longer a Googler; maybe you could help escalate the significance of that problem to the people who make such decisions?

Fair. The work around seems reasonable though all things considered. Knowing the cause of the issue does temper my upset. If one's running in the local directory, there doesn't seem to be another way to avoid it, beyond fairly unambiguous file names. This is very helpful James! Thank you.

Fixes were insufficient as the root issue is https://github.com/golang/protobuf/issues/1122.

Either we need to specify the proto file names differently when in a local directory, or, rename the v1.proto files to be less generic, or both.
Should be fixed by https://github.com/protocolbuffers/protobuf-go/commit/febffdd88e85cb4402205142aaa1a4cc64d0d375.
Turns out we'll fix it in another way too: Removing the pubsub proto in favour of the ones that have cropped up in the beam_runner_api.proto anyway. Aiming to get it in before the next cut.
